Yeah it really surprised
everyone else in my department.

00:12:19.690 --> 00:12:21.900
So we went along, and
at a certain moment

00:12:21.900 --> 00:12:25.630
we thought, back
in the early 90s,

00:12:25.630 --> 00:12:27.270
what you could do
with a website.

00:12:27.270 --> 00:12:31.270
We thought about ways in
which we could use the web

00:12:31.270 --> 00:12:35.530
to give students different
ways, interactive ways,

00:12:35.530 --> 00:12:38.530
of engaging with history and
seeing things for themselves.

00:12:38.530 --> 00:12:40.490
To make points that
we wanted to make.

00:12:40.490 --> 00:12:42.040
The central point
we wanted to make

00:12:42.040 --> 00:12:45.050
was that China was not
a unit of analysis,

00:12:45.050 --> 00:12:46.560
except at the political level.

00:12:46.560 --> 00:12:49.690
That thinking about it as a
single culture was mistaken,

00:12:49.690 --> 00:12:54.280
thinking about all peoples being
the same, thinking about them

00:12:54.280 --> 00:12:57.910
all being, as an email from
one of the students in our DCE

00:12:57.910 --> 00:13:02.620
course said, worker bees and
ants who have no individuality.

00:13:02.620 --> 00:13:05.620
And we tried to break down
assumptions like that.

00:13:05.620 --> 00:13:09.820
So, from there, having
worked on the website

00:13:09.820 --> 00:13:13.120
with people who
are just beginning

00:13:13.120 --> 00:13:19.572
to do that at Harvard, and then
DCE said you could take an FAS

00:13:19.572 --> 00:13:22.030
course and you could put it
online as well, so that's cool,

00:13:22.030 --> 00:13:23.000
let's do that.

00:13:23.000 --> 00:13:25.150
Because we found what
when we had the website,

00:13:25.150 --> 00:13:28.000
we actually had more
students outside of Harvard

00:13:28.000 --> 00:13:30.130
than inside of Harvard,
and they were more

00:13:30.130 --> 00:13:31.860
engaged actually
with the website

00:13:31.860 --> 00:13:33.166
than Harvard students were.

00:13:33.166 --> 00:13:35.040
Because Harvard students
were very motivated,

00:13:35.040 --> 00:13:36.700
said tell me what
the assignment is I

00:13:36.700 --> 00:13:41.150
will go and do exactly that,
and no more very often.

00:13:41.150 --> 00:13:45.250
So we got to the
DCE course and there

00:13:45.250 --> 00:13:47.500
are ways of doing that,
they'd film us then

00:13:47.500 --> 00:13:50.320
we'd have online
sections with the TF,

00:13:50.320 --> 00:13:54.840
but in the course of
that, the TFs were

00:13:54.840 --> 00:13:56.340
sort of interested
in what you could

00:13:56.340 --> 00:13:57.900
do with digital
stuff, kept saying,

00:13:57.900 --> 00:14:01.030
there's so much more we
could do, we should be doing.

00:14:01.030 --> 00:14:05.170
And, being somewhat lazy, my
colleague and I didn't do it.

00:14:05.170 --> 00:14:07.340
But then we heard about
this HarvardX thing

00:14:07.340 --> 00:14:08.660
that was beginning.

00:14:08.660 --> 00:14:11.110
And we said, I happen to
be chair of a committee

00:14:11.110 --> 00:14:14.620
where I was sitting
next to a person who

00:14:14.620 --> 00:14:17.140
had a lot of authority
over HarvardX,

00:14:17.140 --> 00:14:20.530
and I said, you know, if you
would let us take our China

00:14:20.530 --> 00:14:22.990
course, our Chinese
history course,

00:14:22.990 --> 00:14:30.235
and do it as an online course,
if you devote the resource

00:14:30.235 --> 00:14:32.164
to that, we'll devote the time.

00:14:32.164 --> 00:14:33.830
Because this will be
a chance, actually,

00:14:33.830 --> 00:14:36.070
to realize the
promise of this course

00:14:36.070 --> 00:14:38.520
that we could do so
much more digitally

00:14:38.520 --> 00:14:42.420
online and really do right
by our online students.

00:14:42.420 --> 00:14:43.750
That was the idea behind it.

00:14:43.750 --> 00:14:46.560
And so we began, and
I actually offered

00:14:46.560 --> 00:14:48.110
a new undergraduate
course in, how

00:14:48.110 --> 00:14:53.890
do we turn Chinese
history into a MOOC,

00:14:53.890 --> 00:14:57.150
and it was right at the
beginning of HarvardX

00:14:57.150 --> 00:14:59.230
we had no guidance,
no constraints, very

00:14:59.230 --> 00:15:01.960
little support, and
so we just went wild.

00:15:01.960 --> 00:15:05.280
The course last
18 months, right?

00:15:05.280 --> 00:15:10.230
It has 50 modules, had to be
divided into 10 mini courses,

00:15:10.230 --> 00:15:15.140
but we have 500,000
people registering for it.

00:15:15.140 --> 00:15:19.585
In fact, as far as I can
tell from the figures I

00:15:19.585 --> 00:15:21.490
got the other day,
we've had more students

00:15:21.490 --> 00:15:24.760
in that course, and more
people completing it,

00:15:24.760 --> 00:15:28.010
than any course except CS-50.

00:15:28.010 --> 00:15:29.594
So, that was a real success.

00:15:29.594 --> 00:15:31.010
So we said, well,
what we're going

00:15:31.010 --> 00:15:34.282
to do is we actually want this
to have real value at Harvard,

00:15:34.282 --> 00:15:35.740
and we're going to
take this course

00:15:35.740 --> 00:15:37.420
and we're going to
flip the classroom

00:15:37.420 --> 00:15:42.090
and what that means is, we have
our lectures have been done

00:15:42.090 --> 00:15:45.730
and the HarvardX style is what's
called a chunk and test style.

00:15:45.730 --> 00:15:48.790
You know, people's attention
wanders after five or six

00:15:48.790 --> 00:15:50.650
minutes you've got
to tell a joke,

00:15:50.650 --> 00:15:55.840
and then you put an assessment,
you say, are you awake still?

00:15:55.840 --> 00:15:58.660
You'll push this button or
multiple choice question,

00:15:58.660 --> 00:16:01.070
or write a sentence or two.

00:16:01.070 --> 00:16:04.000
And so we said, we'll do
that with our students.

00:16:04.000 --> 00:16:06.380
We'll take our lectures,
and we'll put them on--

00:16:06.380 --> 00:16:08.950
they'll just use NX platform,
the HarvardX platform,

00:16:08.950 --> 00:16:11.590
they'll do that and then when
they come to class, rather

00:16:11.590 --> 00:16:14.290
than us lecturing for
three hours a week

00:16:14.290 --> 00:16:16.270
with a fourth hour
of section, we

00:16:16.270 --> 00:16:19.575
will use that class time to
engage with the students.

00:16:19.575 --> 00:16:20.950
The students always
say they want

00:16:20.950 --> 00:16:22.450
to engage with the
professors, we're

00:16:22.450 --> 00:16:25.030
going to engage with the
students, really intensively.

00:16:25.030 --> 00:16:26.560
We'll have
discussion, we'll have

00:16:26.560 --> 00:16:29.710
things to read and
discuss, my colleague

00:16:29.710 --> 00:16:33.616
had some cool HBS
cases to bring in,

00:16:33.616 --> 00:16:35.740
and he wouldn't have to
lecture anymore, because he

00:16:35.740 --> 00:16:36.900
was a boring lecturer.

00:16:36.900 --> 00:16:39.250
When he lectured,
50% of the students

00:16:39.250 --> 00:16:40.500
would disappear within a week.

00:16:43.450 --> 00:16:47.170
So we went ahead with that.

00:16:47.170 --> 00:16:51.589
Now, we didn't quite understand
that if-- but of course,

00:16:51.589 --> 00:16:53.380
since we wanted students
to get the lecture

00:16:53.380 --> 00:16:54.940
we required them
to do it, and we

00:16:54.940 --> 00:16:57.640
said you have to do it
before you come to class,

00:16:57.640 --> 00:17:00.310
and sometimes that meant two
or three hours of modules

00:17:00.310 --> 00:17:01.740
before you came to class.

00:17:01.740 --> 00:17:02.730
And you had to do
the assessments,

00:17:02.730 --> 00:17:04.938
and we knew because if you
didn't do the assessments,

00:17:04.938 --> 00:17:06.670
that was 20% of your grade.

00:17:06.670 --> 00:17:13.180
And failure to do that on time
put you in a lot of jeopardy.

00:17:13.180 --> 00:17:14.790
So we just thought
this was great,

00:17:14.790 --> 00:17:16.873
we were going to spend our
time with our students,

00:17:16.873 --> 00:17:18.940
we said to our TFs, "You
guys still get paid,

00:17:18.940 --> 00:17:20.650
but we're not going
to have sections,

00:17:20.650 --> 00:17:24.280
because we are teaching the
students the section ourselves.

00:17:24.280 --> 00:17:26.824
The professors are going to
be doing all the teaching."

00:17:30.150 --> 00:17:33.320
So this is a class that had
student ratings in the Q Guide,

00:17:33.320 --> 00:17:36.980
like 4.4, things
like that, where

00:17:36.980 --> 00:17:41.930
I had these fantastic ratings
in the Q guide for my lecturing.

00:17:41.930 --> 00:17:47.150
I think I got, after
the end of this, 2.6.

00:17:47.150 --> 00:17:51.860
In the Q Guide world, this is
like really, really dismal,

00:17:51.860 --> 00:17:53.510
going downhill.

00:17:53.510 --> 00:17:57.190
And the students really
disliked the course.

00:17:57.190 --> 00:18:02.360
And we saw an immediate
drop in enrollment of 50%.

00:18:02.360 --> 00:18:07.290
And my friend, my colleague,
who offered some HBS cases

00:18:07.290 --> 00:18:08.800
and taught them
in the HBS style,

00:18:08.800 --> 00:18:10.830
he did extremely well with that.

00:18:10.830 --> 00:18:13.050
So our relationship reversed.

00:18:13.050 --> 00:18:16.290
For 20 years he had to
get scores behind me,

00:18:16.290 --> 00:18:18.070
he's a very competitive guy.

00:18:18.070 --> 00:18:20.680
And now all of a sudden he had
to look at me and the staff

00:18:20.680 --> 00:18:25.760
management, "It's all right,
you know, you'll get over this."

00:18:25.760 --> 00:18:28.020
And so that was just--

00:18:28.020 --> 00:18:28.900
why did it happen?

00:18:28.900 --> 00:18:32.190
So that's the first question we
asked, so what happened here?

00:18:32.190 --> 00:18:35.520
Because we thought we
were doing a good thing.

00:18:35.520 --> 00:18:37.020
Well, we discovered
a couple things.

00:18:37.020 --> 00:18:39.380
One is, the graduate
students were unhappy,

00:18:39.380 --> 00:18:41.390
because they were being
deprived of a chance

00:18:41.390 --> 00:18:45.560
to interact with students
and be teachers themselves.

00:18:45.560 --> 00:18:47.750
The students were unhappy,
because they actually

00:18:47.750 --> 00:18:49.460
appreciate talking
to graduate students

00:18:49.460 --> 00:18:51.200
more than the professors.

00:18:51.200 --> 00:18:53.690
That's sort of the culture
they've been brought up

00:18:53.690 --> 00:18:57.380
in here at the college.

00:18:57.380 --> 00:19:01.200
They were unhappy
because we cold called.

00:19:01.200 --> 00:19:04.297
We explained the logic
behind cold calling,

00:19:04.297 --> 00:19:05.630
but they were unhappy with that.

00:19:08.340 --> 00:19:10.340
And then the other
thing we found

00:19:10.340 --> 00:19:13.640
was that of course they
did the assessments,

00:19:13.640 --> 00:19:15.860
but that meant that they
had to keep going back

00:19:15.860 --> 00:19:21.350
over the online lecture to make
sure they got the answer right.

00:19:21.350 --> 00:19:26.470
And to get the answer right,
they had to spend more time.

00:19:26.470 --> 00:19:30.420
All of a sudden, their time
on task outside of the class

00:19:30.420 --> 00:19:32.670
doubled.

00:19:32.670 --> 00:19:34.746
They were unhappy.

00:19:34.746 --> 00:19:36.370
And they let us know
they were unhappy,

00:19:36.370 --> 00:19:38.490
and students make a
choice, and they walked.

00:19:41.310 --> 00:19:43.770
So that was bad for the
study of Chinese history.

00:19:43.770 --> 00:19:46.470
If part of your goal
is to get students

00:19:46.470 --> 00:19:50.350
to know about Chinese history
and to think analytically

00:19:50.350 --> 00:19:52.290
about it, that was bad.

00:19:52.290 --> 00:19:55.290
It was bad for us
because it hurt our egos,

00:19:55.290 --> 00:19:58.800
and you can make all
sorts of justifications,

00:19:58.800 --> 00:20:01.670
the students do need
to do more work,

00:20:01.670 --> 00:20:03.530
but they can choose not to.

00:20:03.530 --> 00:20:05.606
It wasn't a required course.

00:20:05.606 --> 00:20:06.980
We know from some
flipped courses

00:20:06.980 --> 00:20:10.589
that are required courses that
they're really successful.

00:20:10.589 --> 00:20:13.130
In terms of learning outcomes,
often the students liked them.

00:20:13.130 --> 00:20:16.970
But this was an elective,
it wasn't a required course.

00:20:16.970 --> 00:20:20.100
So that's a story
of abysmal failure.

00:20:20.100 --> 00:20:25.205
And we made some adjustments,
we put back in sections.

00:20:29.920 --> 00:20:34.110
But still, I can't say that--

00:20:34.110 --> 00:20:38.310
things have not been good.

00:20:38.310 --> 00:20:40.426
They would much prefer
to have a lecture,

00:20:40.426 --> 00:20:42.270
and I'm very good
at giving lectures.

00:20:42.270 --> 00:20:43.560
Right?

00:20:43.560 --> 00:20:51.180
So, we're not going to continue
the course and the new Gen Ed

00:20:51.180 --> 00:20:55.916
program, it doesn't really fit
the Gen Ed standards anyway.

00:20:55.916 --> 00:20:57.540
It's a terrible way
to end your career,

00:20:57.540 --> 00:20:58.539
to think that a course--

00:20:58.539 --> 00:21:00.810
[LAUGHTER]

00:21:00.810 --> 00:21:03.480
That you've just failed.

00:21:03.480 --> 00:21:05.470
So you want success out of this.

00:21:05.470 --> 00:21:07.920
How do we measure success?

00:21:07.920 --> 00:21:10.550
Well, one way that we didn't
talk about enough this morning

00:21:10.550 --> 00:21:16.210
is, surely a measure of success
has to be what students learn.

00:21:16.210 --> 00:21:18.450
Not whether they like us.

00:21:18.450 --> 00:21:20.760
Do students learn more
when they go through this?

00:21:20.760 --> 00:21:22.020
Yes.

00:21:22.020 --> 00:21:24.660
Do they have to do more
work to learn more?

00:21:24.660 --> 00:21:25.740
Yes.

00:21:25.740 --> 00:21:27.840
So there is an
comment right here

00:21:27.840 --> 00:21:32.340
where you say if I do
more time I'll do better,

00:21:32.340 --> 00:21:34.450
but I don't want
to do more time.

00:21:34.450 --> 00:21:37.751
I have my notion of what a core
curriculum course, a Gen Ed

00:21:37.751 --> 00:21:39.750
course should be, how
many hours it should cost,

00:21:39.750 --> 00:21:42.790
and you changed the rules on me.

00:21:42.790 --> 00:21:45.650
So those students who
were on the first course

00:21:45.650 --> 00:21:47.880
have now all graduated,
and this year,

00:21:47.880 --> 00:21:51.140
all of a sudden, our
enrollments doubled.

00:21:51.140 --> 00:21:53.940
And I said, wow, so how
do we account for this?

00:21:53.940 --> 00:21:56.190
Not only did they double,
but the students are active

00:21:56.190 --> 00:21:59.480
and they're enthusiastic
and we have this full room

00:21:59.480 --> 00:22:03.030
and you know just constant
discussion and cold calling,

00:22:03.030 --> 00:22:07.410
no one gets upset by
that, it's just wonderful.

00:22:07.410 --> 00:22:09.570
And so we said, you
know what it is?

00:22:09.570 --> 00:22:16.500
It's the new generation
of students are used to,

00:22:16.500 --> 00:22:20.580
are more accepting of online
stuff, of flipped classrooms,

00:22:20.580 --> 00:22:23.920
of hyper blended learning,
that's what it is.

00:22:23.920 --> 00:22:25.350
And the guys who
remember what it

00:22:25.350 --> 00:22:28.510
used to be like in
the old days are gone.

00:22:28.510 --> 00:22:30.810
And so students come in and
they're having a good time

00:22:30.810 --> 00:22:33.030
and it's just great.

00:22:33.030 --> 00:22:35.512
And so I said that has to be--

00:22:35.512 --> 00:22:37.595
I have no evidence that's
the solution of course--

00:22:37.595 --> 00:22:39.610
but has to be the solution.

00:22:39.610 --> 00:22:44.530
And then, I was talking
to the staff member

00:22:44.530 --> 00:22:47.950
who runs the
undergraduate program

00:22:47.950 --> 00:22:49.830
and said, no, I'm afraid not.

00:22:49.830 --> 00:22:51.330
She said, you know,
they're changing

00:22:51.330 --> 00:22:55.302
the requirements for
undergraduates from the old Gen

00:22:55.302 --> 00:22:58.330
Ed to the new Gen Ed, and so the
freshman and sophomores don't

00:22:58.330 --> 00:23:00.140
have to do it, but the
juniors and seniors

00:23:00.140 --> 00:23:02.050
have to fulfill requirements
of the old days.

00:23:02.050 --> 00:23:07.210
That explains your
doubling in enrollments.

00:23:07.210 --> 00:23:09.880
But what I will
say, I guess this

00:23:09.880 --> 00:23:12.760
is my nod in the
direction of success,

00:23:12.760 --> 00:23:16.980
is that the engagement
with the students

00:23:16.980 --> 00:23:21.500
in that hour and a half
section has been really quite

00:23:21.500 --> 00:23:22.500
extraordinary this year.

00:23:22.500 --> 00:23:24.125
Better than anything
we've seen before.

00:23:24.125 --> 00:23:28.030
But that may just be a
function of having a full room.

00:23:28.030 --> 00:23:29.965
So at the moment, I
don't know whether it's

00:23:29.965 --> 00:23:31.100
a success or failure yet.

00:23:38.150 --> 00:23:40.070
Thank you so much
for sharing that.

00:23:40.070 --> 00:23:41.630
And at the least
from your failure

00:23:41.630 --> 00:23:45.920
came a successful sharing
with the room right here.

00:23:45.920 --> 00:23:47.920
Yeah, if it matters to you.

00:23:47.920 --> 00:23:48.610
Yes.

00:23:48.610 --> 00:23:50.110
So I'll actually
ask everyone again,

00:23:50.110 --> 00:23:53.930
to go back into
your small groups.

00:23:53.930 --> 00:23:55.880
And just take a moment
again to reflect,

00:23:55.880 --> 00:23:57.830
and I don't know what you talked
about in your small groups

00:23:57.830 --> 00:24:00.130
before, if you talked about sort
of more personal little things,

00:24:00.130 --> 00:24:02.960
but if you could take a moment
and, thank you again to Peter

00:24:02.960 --> 00:24:07.610
for really sharing,
reflect on a failure

00:24:07.610 --> 00:24:09.020
in your professional life.

00:24:09.020 --> 00:24:12.100
Something that didn't go the
way you thought it would,

00:24:12.100 --> 00:24:13.017
and what lessons--

00:24:13.017 --> 00:24:14.600
did you just say,
oh that didn't work,

00:24:14.600 --> 00:24:16.016
I'm never trying
it again, or what

00:24:16.016 --> 00:24:17.970
lessons learned came from that?

00:24:17.970 --> 00:24:20.180
And we'll take just
about five or so minutes

00:24:20.180 --> 00:24:22.334
to reflect on that.

00:24:22.334 --> 00:24:23.750
And also thinking
about maybe some

00:24:23.750 --> 00:24:25.569
risks that you
haven't yet taken.

00:24:25.569 --> 00:24:27.110
Risks that didn't
work well and risks

00:24:27.110 --> 00:24:28.520
that you haven't yet taken.

00:24:28.520 --> 00:24:33.320
So, thank you, and just
take a moment to gather.

