00:25:14.530 --> 00:25:18.500
so it seems complicated so
I'm just curious how you--

00:25:18.500 --> 00:25:22.760
So when I'm lecturing, I can
tell whether the students

00:25:22.760 --> 00:25:25.227
are understanding right away.

00:25:25.227 --> 00:25:27.060
I can tell from whether
it's getting across,

00:25:27.060 --> 00:25:30.560
whether my explanation
is working or not.

00:25:30.560 --> 00:25:31.730
And so I want it to work.

00:25:31.730 --> 00:25:33.470
I want them to
understand, right?

00:25:33.470 --> 00:25:34.970
And so if they're
not understanding,

00:25:34.970 --> 00:25:38.090
I know I've done a bad job.

00:25:38.090 --> 00:25:41.210
The second thing is that,
they should be so caught up

00:25:41.210 --> 00:25:43.560
in the problem, or whatever
it is you're talking about,

00:25:43.560 --> 00:25:45.370
that they can start
to anticipate,

00:25:45.370 --> 00:25:47.831
and sometimes
spontaneously a question

00:25:47.831 --> 00:25:50.570
is coming out of the audience.

00:25:50.570 --> 00:25:55.740
And that engagement with that
story is really important.

00:25:55.740 --> 00:26:01.680
And then-- but I shouldn't
take up this time.

00:26:01.680 --> 00:26:04.050
Anybody else?

00:26:04.050 --> 00:26:09.000
You guys can ask
questions, I don't mind.

00:26:09.000 --> 00:26:11.570
I think we were struck by
the lack of commonality

00:26:11.570 --> 00:26:12.840
in our discussion.

00:26:17.250 --> 00:26:20.300
Other tables also had a
similar lack of commonalities?

00:26:24.710 --> 00:26:29.480
I was just-- if I'm
summarizing correctly--

00:26:37.490 --> 00:26:40.470
A professor might try a
novel approach and students,

00:26:40.470 --> 00:26:46.740
for whatever reason, maybe
fear failure or just fear

00:26:46.740 --> 00:26:52.680
of novelty, don't react
well to the faculty's ideas

00:26:52.680 --> 00:26:56.020
and approach and
novel situation.

00:26:56.020 --> 00:27:03.042
And is that because the scenario
is challenging or is not

00:27:03.042 --> 00:27:03.750
well thought out?

00:27:03.750 --> 00:27:07.100
Or is it just the students
that are afraid of novelty?

00:27:09.710 --> 00:27:12.740
Pose that question to you guys.

00:27:12.740 --> 00:27:13.946
Thoughts on--

00:27:13.946 --> 00:27:20.840
I was thinking that one of
the things that's coming out

00:27:20.840 --> 00:27:24.400
is like there are a lot
of different ways to fail.

00:27:24.400 --> 00:27:25.822
[LAUGHTER]

00:27:25.822 --> 00:27:28.714
Are there any commonalities
or categories?

00:27:28.714 --> 00:27:33.460
It did seem like one is
mismatches of expectations.

00:27:33.460 --> 00:27:35.740
And the whole
question of whether we

00:27:35.740 --> 00:27:39.670
could reduce failure and
have more success by thinking

00:27:39.670 --> 00:27:42.910
about expectation setting
in a more sophisticated way,

00:27:42.910 --> 00:27:46.570
whether it's giving instructions
for your very first exercise,

00:27:46.570 --> 00:27:48.874
or the fact that the
expectations of those students,

00:27:48.874 --> 00:27:51.415
they're thinking it should be
like the old curriculum instead

00:27:51.415 --> 00:27:52.373
of the new or whatever.

00:27:52.373 --> 00:27:54.690
I don't know if
that's a category.

00:27:54.690 --> 00:27:57.570
That's great.

00:27:57.570 --> 00:27:59.750
I actually have an reflection.

00:27:59.750 --> 00:28:01.700
I teach language,
beginners Spanish,

00:28:01.700 --> 00:28:05.700
so the failures are
related to the grammar

00:28:05.700 --> 00:28:07.620
and the explanations
and all that.

00:28:07.620 --> 00:28:11.170
But I always have this idea of--

00:28:11.170 --> 00:28:14.530
How we approach the
failure of the students

00:28:14.530 --> 00:28:18.640
because we failed to explain
to them properly what they--

00:28:18.640 --> 00:28:23.520
I see that when I grade a quiz,
and say oh no, I did it wrong.

00:28:23.520 --> 00:28:26.490
It's my fault.
That's a moment where

00:28:26.490 --> 00:28:28.860
you say, how do I do this.

00:28:28.860 --> 00:28:32.490
I mean, grammar is easy, I don't
know about all the disciplines,

00:28:32.490 --> 00:28:34.120
language is easy to do.

00:28:34.120 --> 00:28:37.258
I know, but-- I don't
know what you think.

00:28:41.202 --> 00:28:42.188
Reflections on that?

00:28:47.480 --> 00:28:50.819
Just, a little bit of
what you're saying--

00:28:50.819 --> 00:28:52.610
piggy backing off of
what Peter was saying,

00:28:52.610 --> 00:28:54.870
our small table
discussion, I think

00:28:54.870 --> 00:28:57.650
a commonalty is the success
part of the failure, right?

00:28:57.650 --> 00:28:59.630
And it requires a
vulnerability just

00:28:59.630 --> 00:29:02.960
to take a look at, whether
it's Q scores or attendance,

00:29:02.960 --> 00:29:05.870
and wonder why, and not
just wondering but actively

00:29:05.870 --> 00:29:07.900
go after why, and
to keep digging

00:29:07.900 --> 00:29:10.620
until you can get that answer.

00:29:10.620 --> 00:29:13.520
You know, whether you are a
faculty member, an instructor,

00:29:13.520 --> 00:29:16.526
or an academic
professional, you know,

00:29:16.526 --> 00:29:17.900
opening yourself
up for feedback,

00:29:17.900 --> 00:29:23.670
I think that's tough to do, but
people care enough to do it.

00:29:23.670 --> 00:29:25.644
Thanks.

00:29:25.644 --> 00:29:27.925
Final comments?

00:29:27.925 --> 00:29:28.966
All right, I'm going to--

00:29:28.966 --> 00:29:29.740
oh.

00:29:29.740 --> 00:29:34.560
So I just want to sort of
reiterate the comment--

00:29:34.560 --> 00:29:39.310
my assumption is that when I
deal with a student who either

00:29:39.310 --> 00:29:42.960
thinks that she isn't
getting what's going on,

00:29:42.960 --> 00:29:45.780
or seems to me
not to be getting,

00:29:45.780 --> 00:29:48.420
those are two
different categories,

00:29:48.420 --> 00:29:52.410
my assumption is that's my
problem, not her problem.

00:29:52.410 --> 00:30:02.520
And I've got to figure out
where the mismatch how it arose.

00:30:02.520 --> 00:30:04.420
I don't always know
exactly what it

00:30:04.420 --> 00:30:08.630
means partly that it
actually goes back to your,

00:30:08.630 --> 00:30:10.887
everybody gets A
minuses here, you know,

00:30:10.887 --> 00:30:13.095
back to the measure of the
students at the Law School

00:30:13.095 --> 00:30:14.920
are pretty talented.

00:30:14.920 --> 00:30:20.040
And so it probably is the case
that if student isn't getting

00:30:20.040 --> 00:30:24.870
something I'm trying to do,
it's on me, not on the student.

00:30:24.870 --> 00:30:30.050
So anyway, again, figuring out
how to respond to that problem

00:30:30.050 --> 00:30:33.130
is the hard part.

00:30:33.130 --> 00:30:36.690
So I think the magic word
for today is mismatch.

00:30:36.690 --> 00:30:40.000
We're looking at mismatch
between expectations

00:30:40.000 --> 00:30:42.310
amongst faculty and
students, mismatch

00:30:42.310 --> 00:30:44.200
between what I
think I'm teaching

00:30:44.200 --> 00:30:47.470
and what I think my
students are comprehending,

00:30:47.470 --> 00:30:49.720
and then, basically,
to top it all off,

00:30:49.720 --> 00:30:52.420
is how comfortable am
I trying to figure out

00:30:52.420 --> 00:30:56.780
where that mismatch lies, and
what am I going to do about it?

00:30:56.780 --> 00:31:00.009
So with this I'm now going
pass it over to Randy who--

00:31:00.009 --> 00:31:02.050
I always have to look
because it's a lot of words

00:31:02.050 --> 00:31:03.220
and I always mix them up--

00:31:03.220 --> 00:31:05.514
case based
collaborative learning.

00:31:05.514 --> 00:31:07.210
Correct.

00:31:07.210 --> 00:31:09.580
So they're doing some novel
stuff at the medical school,

00:31:09.580 --> 00:31:12.010
so I just want him to
kind of talk about what's

00:31:12.010 --> 00:31:14.950
making them take this risk,
what support you've had,

00:31:14.950 --> 00:31:16.630
and kind of what
you've learned so far.

00:31:22.890 --> 00:31:25.190
So thanks very much.

00:31:25.190 --> 00:31:30.330
So I've taught at the medical
school for about 14 years now,

00:31:30.330 --> 00:31:32.750
and have been fortunate
to work with a fantastic

00:31:32.750 --> 00:31:34.044
group of first year students.

00:31:34.044 --> 00:31:35.460
So in the courses
that I've taught

00:31:35.460 --> 00:31:38.680
I typically teach very
early in the curriculum,

00:31:38.680 --> 00:31:42.410
so they're just transitioning
to medical school and kind

00:31:42.410 --> 00:31:45.480
of getting used to
drinking from a fire hose

00:31:45.480 --> 00:31:48.800
as the analogy goes.

00:31:48.800 --> 00:31:50.780
And so I think we
have an opportunity

00:31:50.780 --> 00:31:54.500
to really understand
how students

00:31:54.500 --> 00:31:56.670
react to this sort of
change in their learning.

00:31:56.670 --> 00:32:00.110
As undergraduates,
you know, students

00:32:00.110 --> 00:32:01.610
have the luxury of time.

00:32:01.610 --> 00:32:04.850
In medical school, it
goes at a very fast pace.

00:32:04.850 --> 00:32:06.740
And so one of the
challenges we face

00:32:06.740 --> 00:32:11.167
is really thinking about how do
we keep students engaged sort

00:32:11.167 --> 00:32:14.000
of day in and day out
with a curriculum that

00:32:14.000 --> 00:32:16.850
is a lot of material
and a lot of content.

00:32:16.850 --> 00:32:19.010
And I think that's
one of the things that

00:32:19.010 --> 00:32:22.150
drove the curriculum reform
at the medical school,

00:32:22.150 --> 00:32:25.460
and sort of switched to
this so-called case based

00:32:25.460 --> 00:32:27.830
collaborative learning
which really was, I think,

00:32:27.830 --> 00:32:30.400
a nice outgrowth of the
work of many people,

00:32:30.400 --> 00:32:32.810
including Rick Schwartzstein
and others at the school,

00:32:32.810 --> 00:32:34.370
and really thinking
about, how can we

00:32:34.370 --> 00:32:36.740
best engage our learners.

00:32:36.740 --> 00:32:40.350
So the story I wanted to
tell is sort of my experience

00:32:40.350 --> 00:32:42.890
in this process.

00:32:42.890 --> 00:32:46.010
And sort of thinking about
how we might do this, how

00:32:46.010 --> 00:32:48.440
we might take on this approach.

00:32:48.440 --> 00:32:52.522
In the old course that I
taught, it was a mix of lecture,

00:32:52.522 --> 00:32:54.980
so they'd have a couple of
hours of lecture in the morning,

00:32:54.980 --> 00:32:59.540
and then a 90 minute small group
discussion in groups of eight.

00:32:59.540 --> 00:33:01.280
And one of the
logistic challenges

00:33:01.280 --> 00:33:06.450
that we face with a class of
160 is recruiting 22 discussion

00:33:06.450 --> 00:33:07.790
leaders.

00:33:07.790 --> 00:33:09.435
These are all faculty,
but faculty kind

00:33:09.435 --> 00:33:12.140
of across the school.

00:33:12.140 --> 00:33:14.870
Getting a uniformity of
experience for that process

00:33:14.870 --> 00:33:16.880
was a challenge,
and that was one

00:33:16.880 --> 00:33:19.720
of the motivations for thinking
about other types of formats.

00:33:22.740 --> 00:33:26.100
So I would say our curriculum
has been running about three

00:33:26.100 --> 00:33:29.420
years now, I'd say about
five or six years ago,

00:33:29.420 --> 00:33:31.800
and it's amazing how I'm
hearing echoes of what

00:33:31.800 --> 00:33:34.620
Peter said in terms of failure.

00:33:34.620 --> 00:33:36.130
We decided to give this a try.

00:33:36.130 --> 00:33:37.840
Let's try flipping a session.

00:33:37.840 --> 00:33:41.400
So again typically what we were
doing is lecturing for students

00:33:41.400 --> 00:33:43.980
for a couple of hours
then a day or so later

00:33:43.980 --> 00:33:47.220
they'd go and discuss the
material in their small groups.

00:33:47.220 --> 00:33:49.470
And we thought, well,
let's flip this around.

00:33:49.470 --> 00:33:51.470
You know, we're recording
all these lectures,

00:33:51.470 --> 00:33:53.470
half the students aren't
coming to our lectures,

00:33:53.470 --> 00:33:55.860
they're watching
the videos anyway,

00:33:55.860 --> 00:34:00.300
surely they'll find this
an interesting exercise.

00:34:00.300 --> 00:34:02.460
And so what we told
them was, for two

00:34:02.460 --> 00:34:05.990
of the sessions in the course,
instead of having lectures

00:34:05.990 --> 00:34:10.170
we are going to have them watch
last year's lecture online,

00:34:10.170 --> 00:34:12.360
which we made available to them.

00:34:12.360 --> 00:34:17.292
And we said, you know, do that
over the weekend, hint hint.

00:34:17.292 --> 00:34:19.620
Do that over the
weekend and then come in

00:34:19.620 --> 00:34:22.031
on Monday, and
instead of lecturing,

00:34:22.031 --> 00:34:24.030
we're going to work through
a series of problems

00:34:24.030 --> 00:34:27.889
together as a large group.

00:34:27.889 --> 00:34:30.710
And so gave this a
try, came out with what

00:34:30.710 --> 00:34:33.650
I thought were some really
interesting questions that

00:34:33.650 --> 00:34:38.360
would require them to apply
their knowledge in this format.

00:34:38.360 --> 00:34:44.110
And I would say it was
met with a lot of silence.

00:34:44.110 --> 00:34:46.730
Trying to get the students
to participate and answer

00:34:46.730 --> 00:34:51.699
questions felt to me
like pulling teeth.

00:34:51.699 --> 00:34:53.199
So that was the first session.

00:34:53.199 --> 00:34:57.290
And then the second session,
I would say about a third

00:34:57.290 --> 00:35:00.490
of the class didn't
even show up.

00:35:00.490 --> 00:35:02.970
I'm like, what is going on here?

00:35:02.970 --> 00:35:04.690
And so we then--

00:35:04.690 --> 00:35:07.400
I don't know if Ed
remembers this at all--

00:35:07.400 --> 00:35:10.050
but we basically had to have
a class meeting after this

00:35:10.050 --> 00:35:13.170
and talk about professionalism
and the importance of showing

00:35:13.170 --> 00:35:16.436
up to class, and that got
into a big debate about, well,

00:35:16.436 --> 00:35:18.060
you know, I'm a
student I should really

00:35:18.060 --> 00:35:21.410
decide what approach for
learning works best for me,

00:35:21.410 --> 00:35:22.510
kind of thing.

00:35:22.510 --> 00:35:24.305
So it was a disaster.

00:35:24.305 --> 00:35:25.180
I mean it really was.

00:35:25.180 --> 00:35:26.740
I'm like, what is
this flipped class?

00:35:26.740 --> 00:35:27.730
Like, this is a mess.

00:35:30.280 --> 00:35:32.610
I mean I just really
didn't know what to make

00:35:32.610 --> 00:35:35.190
of it, to be honest with you.

00:35:35.190 --> 00:35:37.440
And so I guess the
question is why do we

00:35:37.440 --> 00:35:39.230
keep pursuing this approach?

00:35:39.230 --> 00:35:41.520
While other faculty
were experimenting

00:35:41.520 --> 00:35:44.100
with this method
in different ways,

00:35:44.100 --> 00:35:47.190
we ran a pilot
the following year

00:35:47.190 --> 00:35:50.820
where we took a group
of about 40 students,

00:35:50.820 --> 00:35:55.500
sitting in a room like this,
working through questions

00:35:55.500 --> 00:35:56.160
in that format.

00:35:56.160 --> 00:35:59.100
That worked much better
with a group of 40.

00:35:59.100 --> 00:36:01.200
Really what I recognize
in retrospect,

00:36:01.200 --> 00:36:05.100
was really the key
difference was context.

00:36:05.100 --> 00:36:07.170
That-- and I think this
is really the message--

00:36:07.170 --> 00:36:10.549
that if you're going to take
chances and do experiments,

00:36:10.549 --> 00:36:12.090
and if the experiments
fail, you have

00:36:12.090 --> 00:36:14.460
to go back and understand
why the experiment failed.

00:36:14.460 --> 00:36:16.440
The reason the first
experiment failed

00:36:16.440 --> 00:36:19.460
was that these were students
who were used to learning

00:36:19.460 --> 00:36:21.230
in a particular way.

00:36:21.230 --> 00:36:23.850
That was actually working
pretty well for them.

00:36:23.850 --> 00:36:25.260
And then we said
whoa, we're just

00:36:25.260 --> 00:36:27.134
going to change up a
couple of these sessions

00:36:27.134 --> 00:36:29.320
and see if this
is a better idea.

00:36:29.320 --> 00:36:31.020
Think you take something
that ultimately

00:36:31.020 --> 00:36:35.570
can work in its own context
but take it out of context,

00:36:35.570 --> 00:36:38.082
and try it this way, it
can be a real disaster.

00:36:38.082 --> 00:36:40.290
And so I don't think it was
so much about the content

00:36:40.290 --> 00:36:42.500
or the format or the
flipping or so forth,

00:36:42.500 --> 00:36:44.700
but really about
the larger context.

00:36:44.700 --> 00:36:46.620
And, you know, we
now have a curriculum

00:36:46.620 --> 00:36:50.479
that's almost exclusively
flipped sessions

00:36:50.479 --> 00:36:51.520
for the medical students.

00:36:51.520 --> 00:36:55.292
And they do all the prep
work, they work really hard,

00:36:55.292 --> 00:36:57.000
they come to the
sessions, they're really

00:36:57.000 --> 00:36:58.740
very engaged and motivated.

00:36:58.740 --> 00:37:00.930
I think the faculty
are enjoying this,

00:37:00.930 --> 00:37:02.910
and so I think we're
confident that this kind

00:37:02.910 --> 00:37:06.480
of flipped classroom format
can work for medical students,

00:37:06.480 --> 00:37:08.880
but that sure isn't the
conclusion I would have drawn

00:37:08.880 --> 00:37:11.250
from our one pilot experiment.

00:37:11.250 --> 00:37:13.020
So I have to say
the lesson that I've

00:37:13.020 --> 00:37:15.660
learned from this is, pilots
are critical and important

00:37:15.660 --> 00:37:16.970
and we learn from them.

00:37:16.970 --> 00:37:20.050
But you also have to really
interpret them properly.

00:37:20.050 --> 00:37:22.740
And this notion
of context and how

00:37:22.740 --> 00:37:25.540
do you experiment in a
course, is a challenge.

00:37:25.540 --> 00:37:27.580
I mean, should
course pilots really

00:37:27.580 --> 00:37:31.770
be pilots within a course
or of a whole course?

00:37:31.770 --> 00:37:34.380
Because maybe you can't
draw very broad conclusions

00:37:34.380 --> 00:37:37.657
from doing specific experiments,
because the students have

00:37:37.657 --> 00:37:40.352
a certain set of expectations.

00:37:40.352 --> 00:37:42.810
So, in any case, that was the
story that I wanted to share.

00:37:42.810 --> 00:37:47.070
I think experimentation is good,
failure you can learn from,

00:37:47.070 --> 00:37:49.820
but I guess, keep plowing ahead.

00:37:55.394 --> 00:37:56.810
So with that, we're
actually going

00:37:56.810 --> 00:37:59.480
to ask you guys to
think about a risk

00:37:59.480 --> 00:38:04.300
that you haven't taken, but want
to take within the next year.

00:38:04.300 --> 00:38:05.930
Ideally we want you
to write it down

00:38:05.930 --> 00:38:09.040
if you're even up for it,
verbalize it with a partner.

00:38:09.040 --> 00:38:10.130
You know, the whole thing,
if you write it down

00:38:10.130 --> 00:38:12.421
you're more willing to do
it, if you tell it to someone

00:38:12.421 --> 00:38:14.250
you're even more
willing to do it.

00:38:14.250 --> 00:38:16.670
So with that, again,
think about a risk

00:38:16.670 --> 00:38:19.300
that you want to take
within the next year.

00:38:19.300 --> 00:38:21.630
And figure out a plan
to make that happen.

00:38:21.630 --> 00:38:23.490
And we want to help
you make that happen.

00:38:23.490 --> 00:38:27.110
So on the little note cards
that you have at your tables,

00:38:27.110 --> 00:38:30.320
just write down resources
that you might want

00:38:30.320 --> 00:38:31.880
to help you take this risk.

00:38:34.640 --> 00:38:37.460
In these packets as well we've
compiled a bunch of resources

00:38:37.460 --> 00:38:37.980
as well.

00:38:37.980 --> 00:38:41.130
So there is just some
Harvard specific sites,

00:38:41.130 --> 00:38:44.750
the top helped Instructional
Moves just came out,

00:38:44.750 --> 00:38:45.930
it's really cool.

00:38:45.930 --> 00:38:48.380
And then school
